{{italic title}} The '''''Cupid''''' was a sculpture created by Renaissance artist [[Michelangelo]], which he artificially aged to make it look like an antique on the advice of Lorenzo di Pierfrancesco. It was this sculpture which first brought him to the attention of patrons in [[Rome]]. The work is now lost.<ref>Entry on "Cupid," ''The Classical Tradition'' (Harvard University Press, 2010), p. 245; Stefania Macioe, "Caravaggio and the Role of Classical Models," in ''The Rediscovery of Antiquity: The Role of the Artist'' (Collegium Hyperboreum, 2003), pp. 437–438.</ref>
==''Sleeping Cupid''== In 1496, Michelangelo made a sleeping [[cupid]] figure and treated it with acidic earth to make it seem ancient. He then sold it to a dealer, Baldassare del Milanese, who in turn sold it to [[Raffaele Riario|Cardinal Riario of San Giorgio]] who later learned of the fraud and demanded his money back. However, Michelangelo was permitted to keep his share of the money.<ref name="aaa">{{cite web|author=Sheila Gibson Stoodley |url=http://www.artsandantique.net/Articles/Miscellaneous/Featured-Misadventures-in-Collecting.asp |title=Misadventures in Collecting |publisher=''Arts and Antiques'' |date=August 2008 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.museumofhoaxes.com/hoax/archive/permalink/michelangelos_cupid/ |title= Michelangelo's Cupid |publisher= Museum of Hoaxes |accessdate= 2010-01-03}}</ref> When Michelangelo offered to take the sculpture back from Baldassarre, the latter refused, saying he would rather destroy it.<ref>{{cite book |author= Rona Goffen |title= Renaissance rivals: Michelangelo, Leonardo, Rafael, Titian |publisher= Yale University Press |year= 2004 |page= 409, note 83}}</ref>
The ''Cupid'' was a significant work in establishing the reputation of the young Michelangelo, who was about 20 years old at the time.<ref>Deborah Parker, ''Michelangelo and the Art of Letter Writing'' (Cambridge University Press, 2010), p. 11; Rona Goffen, ''Renaissance Rivals: Michelangelo, Leonardo, Raphael, Titian'' ([[Yale University Press]], 2002, 2004), p. 95.</ref> The sculpture was later donated by [[Cesare Borgia]] to [[Isabella d'Este]], and was probably collected by [[Charles I of England]] when all the [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] collections were bought and taken to [[London]] in the seventeenth century.<ref name="aaa" />
In 1698, the ''Cupid'' was probably destroyed in the great fire in the [[Palace of Whitehall]], [[London]].<ref name="aaa" />
==''Standing Cupid''== Another sculpture of Cupid, in a standing position, was created for Riario's banker, Jacopo Galli.<ref>Umberto Baldini, ''Michelangelo scultore'', Rizzoli, Milano 1973, pp. 90-91.</ref>
