{{Other places}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Le Pinacle |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = Le Pinacle Jersey.jpg |alt = |location = [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]] |region = [[Channel Islands]] |coordinates = {{coord|49.2476|-2.2530|region:JE_type:landmark_scale:50000|display=inline,title}} |epochs = Neolithic–Roman |type = |public_access = Yes |condition = |website = }}
'''Le Pinacle''' is a protruding pinnacle of rock, at the coastal edge of a [[Les Landes]] in the north-west of [[Jersey]],<ref>[http://search.jerseyheritage.org/detail.aspx?parentpriref=110179032 Ordnance survey map of part of Cueillette de Vinchelez , St Ouen including the rifle range, model aircraft airfield, Le Beau Vallet and Le Pinacle, plan no 3/6]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> with remains and ruins at its base dating from five periods including the [[Neolithic]] and [[Chalcolithic]] periods, the [[Bronze Age]], and the [[Iron Age]]. There is also evidence of a rectangular [[Gallo-Roman religion|Gallo-Roman temple]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeremy Percival |url=http://www.prehistoricjersey.net/Le_Pinacle.shtml |title=Le Pinacle |publisher=Prehistoricjersey.net |date= |accessdate=2012-10-13}}</ref>
==Dolerite== The [[Diabase|dolerite]] [[stratum]] has been mined, and used to make axe heads during the Neolithic period and Bronze Age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mark-patton.co.uk/id2.html |title=Full List of Publications |publisher=Mark-patton.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-10-13}}</ref>
==Megalith== [[File:L'Êta La Rocque-Ho Jèrri 2010.jpg|thumb|Le Pinacle is visible in the distance (far left)]] The megalithic rock is a natural formation, and a prominent landmark which can be seen from St Ouen's bay.
[[File:Lé Pinnacl'ye Jèrri b.jpg|thumb|The remains of the Roman temple can be seen in this photo]]
